      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is fundamentally rooted in the idea that the Constitution is a fixed document, not a living text subject to modern political whims. Proponents argue that the Founders intended a specific meaning for the text at the time of ratification, and judges must adhere to that original public meaning. This approach prevents unelected judges from imposing their personal policy preferences onto the law. Therefore, originalism ensures judicial restraint and fidelity to the democratic will expressed by the framers.",
