    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but i've been seeing a lot of stuff online saying that originalism is basically just a way for conservative judges to push a specific agenda because they can just pick whatever historical era suits them. how do scholars respond to the critique that it's more about politics than actual law?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics who claim originalism is merely a political tool are fundamentally undermining the entire concept of constitutionalism. Originalists argue that adhering to the original meaning is the *only* way to prevent the judiciary from becoming a super-legislature that constantly rewrites the law based on current social trends. To suggest it's purely political ignores the rigorous historical methodology required to ascertain what the text *actually* meant to the people who ratified it.",
      "source": "target",
