      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The perceived ambiguity in historical interpretation is a weakness of the *originalism* methodology itself, not a refutation of its core principle. While historians may disagree on nuances, the goal of originalism is to find the dominant, shared understanding of the text at the time, not to satisfy every academic debate. Furthermore, the alternative—allowing judges to simply invent meaning based on contemporary feelings—is far more dangerous to the rule of law.",
      "source": "target",
